a_rubin@dsg4.dse.beckman.com (Arthur Rubin) writes:
> ...
>(One of) the RSA/PKP patents covers use of polynomials modulo primes for
>the purpose of encryption (it might be restricted to public-key encryption;
>I don't remember).  (I think it covers digital signatures also, but I
>could be mistaken.)  (Most of) PGP has a non-infringing use; a
>reproducable pseudo-random number generator.  (It may not be good at
>that, but it is a use).  Hence distributing it is probably not illegal as
>contributory infringement.
> ...

Don't forget that PGP can also be used to simply encrypt files:

	pgp -c <filename>

for safekeeping on your own disk (not for transmission).  If you are
doing this for personal (non-business) use, then the IDEA patent
holders don't mind, and no RSA is being used at all.

